SIMPLE: luna
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Luna
<hw>Lu"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.; akin to
<ets>lucere</ets> to shine. See <er>Light</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Lune</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The moon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Alchemy)</fld> <def>Silver.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Luna cornea</b></col> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld>, <cd>horn
silver, or fused silver chloride, a tough, brown, translucent mass; --
so called from its resemblance to horn.</cd> -- <col><b>Luna
moth</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very large and beautiful
American moth (<spn>Actias luna</spn>). Its wings are delicate light
green, with a stripe of purple along the front edge of the anterior
wings, the other margins being edged with pale yellow. Each wing has a
lunate spot surrounded by rings of light yellow, blue, and black. The
caterpillar commonly feeds on the hickory, sassafras, and
maple.</cd></cs></p>

<p><-- Fig. of Luna moth -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lunacy</ent>⟦br⟧
